{"id":14880740,"mediaExerciseId":"5d03328a-ad6f-4295-8608-d4c0bb984c32","exerciseName":"1","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5971788,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to identify what liquidity measures and explain the pros and cons of high and low liquidity.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/cae1d511d3be4e0e464c917f69934812/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/cae1d511d3be4e0e464c917f69934812/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Generally, **liquidity** refers to the capacity of an entity to pay its obligations as they fall due. Finance-wise, it tells whether a business has sufficient assets to settle its currently maturing liabilities. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":105,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/85aaea78866e86c9846928cb904112db/lateximg_large.png","width":1017},"regular":{"height":53,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/85aaea78866e86c9846928cb904112db/lateximg.png","width":509}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"In a balance sheet, entities arrange accounts commonly based on their liquidity. After cash, other **assets** follow according to their easy convertibility to cash. Similarly, **liabilities** are listed based on the timing of the payment - being the obligation with the soonest settlement comes first.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/c9bdee5c8b3f92c4e901177599cc6d91/lateximg_large.png","width":1055},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/c9bdee5c8b3f92c4e901177599cc6d91/lateximg.png","width":527}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Business liquidity comes with particular **strengths and fallbacks**. A highly liquid entity **can pay its debts** because of its cash and other assets that are available for payment. Businesses are **less likely to encounter bankruptcy** if they have more liquid resources at hand - more funds available to suffice business operations.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/6bb4b333f7f180a1e25eb53ca59ba7c8/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/6bb4b333f7f180a1e25eb53ca59ba7c8/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"On the other hand, too much cash holdings could mean lost earnings. Practically speaking, if someone holds their money in their pocket rather than saving it in a bank, interest earned from savings is foregone. Keeping cash and other liquid assets on hand may result in **missed profit opportunities**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/6e5dffbf7816a768d29be622ff3eb44c/lateximg_large.png","width":1042},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/6e5dffbf7816a768d29be622ff3eb44c/lateximg.png","width":522}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"Liquidity is essential for keeping the business capable of operating in the future. Managements must make ways to **analyze the pros and cons** of liquid assets and **develop strategies** to maximize the earning capacity of their resources.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":136,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/7fc165fcb9beac206a3327c23735d7f6/lateximg_large.png","width":998},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/b77e79632f3b8536fcad1407707da565/7fc165fcb9beac206a3327c23735d7f6/lateximg.png","width":500}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"62e326c0-0179-46a7-8643-6d78810b773f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6},{"id":5897989,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to discuss the liquidity and explain the trade-off a firm faces between high-liquidity and low-liquidity levels.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Liquidity** measures how quickly an asset or security can be converted into ready cash without affecting its market price. The higher the liquidity, the easier it is to meet financial obligations. \n\nHowever, liquidity has an opportunity cost. In contrast, other companies invest in illiquid but productive assets that could give them higher returns. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/2df054eb72d365383502b0998c79fc32/a9dbd7e7b609d3ee0f7fe20e7fe749d9/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/2df054eb72d365383502b0998c79fc32/a9dbd7e7b609d3ee0f7fe20e7fe749d9/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"d52688b3-60c7-4171-b231-0f8764e89f0a","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880741,"exerciseName":"2","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-2-733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038"},{"id":14880742,"exerciseName":"3","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-3-ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880739,"exerciseName":"4","page":39,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f90c6c1b-923b-462e-b80b-4336613caea3","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-4-f90c6c1b-923b-462e-b80b-4336613caea3"}],"_webUrl":"